SIMPLE: steady
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Steady
<hw>Stead"y</hw> <pr>(-⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Steadier</adjf>
<pr>(-⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Steadiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>stedig</ets>
sterile, barren, <ets>stae⟦edh⟧⟦edh⟧ig</ets>, steady (in
<ets>gestae⟦edh⟧⟦edh⟧ig</ets>), D. <ets>stedig</ets>, <ets>stadig</ets>,
<ets>steeg</ets>, G. <ets>st⟦aum⟧tig</ets>, <ets>stetig</ets>. See
<er>Stead</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Firm in standing
or position; not tottering or shaking; fixed; firm.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
softest, <xex>steadiest</xex> plume.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Keble.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their feet <qex>steady</qex>, their hands diligent, their eyes
watchful, and their hearts resolute.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Constant in feeling, purpose, or pursuit; not
fickle, changeable, or wavering; not easily moved or persuaded to alter
a purpose; resolute; <as>as, a man <ex>steady</ex> in his principles, in
his purpose, or in the pursuit of an object</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Regular; constant; undeviating; uniform; <as>as, the
<ex>steady</ex> course of the sun; a <ex>steady</ex> breeze of
wind.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Fixed; regular; uniform; undeviating; invariable;
unremitted; stable.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Steady rest</b></col> <fld>(Mach)</fld>, <cd>a rest in a
turning lathe, to keep a long piece of work from
trembling.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steady</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Steady
<hw>Stead"y</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Steadied</conjf> <pr>(-⟦icr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Steadying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make steady; to hold or keep
from shaking, reeling, or falling; to make or keep firm; to support; to
make constant, regular, or resolute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steady</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Steady
<hw>Stead"y</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become steady; to regain a
steady position or state; to move steadily.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without a breeze, without a tide,⟦br⟧
She <qex>steadies</qex> with upright keel.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steak</ent>⟦br⟧
